1.401
log
@a few choices on the U+007FU+009F issue
@
text
@d1 1
a1 1
RCSID: $MirOS: www/data/wlog-10.inc,v 1.400 2012/12/01 20:31:28 tg Exp $
d9334 1
a9334 1
Date: 01.12.2012 20:02
d9370 3
d9374 1
a9374 1
 afterwards. Ive got a forth proposal which changes acceptance rules 
d9384 2
a9385 3
 not needed for U+0020U+D7FF and U+E000U+FFFD after all, though I was
 almost adding a recommendation to escape U+007FU+009F always; thought
 on this is welcome via <a href="@@@@RELPATH@@@@irc.htm">IRC</a> or eMail).
d9392 10
a9401 9
<p style="font-size:small;">Some more on the U+007FU+009F issue: might
 want to always escape them. ECMA says to never escape them; an idea is
 to escape them only if indenting (so <tt>{"foo":"bar"}</tt> gets those
 C1 control characters as-is, <tt>{"foo":"bar"}</tt> escapes them)
 but we might pass the condensed (nn-indented) form to e.g. a database
 which may or may not like them. This isnt about binary (as JSON isnt
 binary-safe anyway; probably best to just use base64 and let the outer
 layers worry about compression) but C1 control characters  C0 already
 are always escaped.</p>
@


